<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="type species">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Type species.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Paratropididae" genus="Anisaspis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anisaspis tuberculata" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculata">Anisaspis tuberculata</taxonomicName>
Simon, 1892, deposited in NHM, examined.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Paratropididae" genus="Anisaspis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anisaspis" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Anisaspis</taxonomicName>
differs from other paratropidid genera by the presence of only two spinnerets (PLS) (Figure 1D) and all legs with only two tarsal claws (STC), males without tibial apophysis and palpal bulb with sinuous embolus (Figure 1E, F). PLS relatively long (Figure 1A, B). Females remain unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The specimen described as holotype female of 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. tuberculata" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="tuberculata">A. tuberculata</taxonomicName>
is actually a juvenile specimen. Therefore, females of this genus remain unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
